04654nam a22006975i 9781400884575DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20161996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008845757 a10.1515/97814008845752doi  a(DE-B1597)477793  a(OCoLC)979579367  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBL1139.242.S86bE5 1996eb 7aREL0320302bisacsh04a294.5/9220452122304aThe Rāmāyaṇa of Vālmīki: An Epic of Ancient India, Volume V :bSundarakāṇḍa /ced. by Robert P. Goldman, Sally J. Sutherland Goldman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (608 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Library of Asian Translations ;v14700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tPreface -- tGuide to Sanskrit Pronunciation -- tPart I. Introduction -- t1. The Position of the Sundarakāṇḍa -- t2. Synopsis of the Sundarakāṇḍa -- t3. The Structure and Contents of the Sundarakāṇḍa -- t4. The Characters of the Sundarakāṇḍa -- t5. A Tale of Three Cities: Ayodhyā, Kiṣkindhā, and Lan̄kā -- t6. The Name of the Sundarakāṇḍa -- t7. The Destiny of the Sundarakāṇḍa -- t8. Text, Translation, and Commentaries -- tPart II. Sundarakāṇḍa -- tPart III. Notes -- tGlossary of Important Sanskrit Words, Proper Nouns, and Epithets -- tBibliography of Works Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fifth and most popular book of the Ramayana of Valmiki, the Sundarakanda, recounts the adventures of the monkey hero Hanuman in leaping across the ocean to the island citadel of Lanka. Once there, he scours the city for the abducted Princess Siti. The poet vividly describes the opulence of the court of the demon king, Ravana, the beauty of his harem, and the hideous deformity of Sita's wardresses. After witnessing Sita's stern rejection of Ravana's blandishments, Hanuman reveals himself to the princess and restores her hope of rescue. The great monkey then wreaks havoc on the royal park and fights a series of hair-raising battles with Ravana's generals. Permitting himself to be captured by the warrior Indrajit, Hanuman is led into the presence of Ravana, whom he admonishes for his lechery. His tail is set ablaze, but he escapes his bonds and leaping from rooftop to rooftop, sets fire to the city. Taking leave of Sita, Hanuman once more leaps the ocean to rejoin his monkey companions. This is the fifth volume translated from the critical edition of the Valmiki Ramayana. It contains an extensive introduction, exhaustive notes, and a comprehensive bibliography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEpic poetry, Sanskrit. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / Sacred Writings.2bisacsh1 aGoldman, Robert P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldman, Sally J. Sutherland, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140088457540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400884575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400884575.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK